s=usertitle>MithMarr Squire</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#006400>(1/22/02 3:58:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsfrm40.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=205.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_cry.gif" align=absmiddle>  Is it class envy or righteous defense of the status quo?</span><hr size=1> First of I'd like to say that I read some of the different class boards, general EQ boards and some guild boards and that I don't intend to flame anyone, EQ wide or MM specific, nor to start a flame war threat.<br>
<br>
Since the release of SoL - remembering that the melee intra-balance patch was a while before that - I have seen guilds call for nerfs of spells of another class and now I see several members of a class call for nerfs of other classes and a clear call for not touching the most frustrating bottleneck for a certain priest class. I am not talking about nerfs which VI did allready as a reaction to their own observation (e.g. the Deep and the Longsword of Etheral Energy).<br>
<br>
Namely it was the nerf of the Paladin spell Thunder of Karana (ToK) which would have given a powerfull role to this class, a position of very-nice-to-have against some mobs but not a must-have. A role that every class should have in my eyes, while still having a status that some classes lack it at all, some have and some exceed to a must-have-position (of at least one player of that class per group or only per raid).<br>
Now it seems that the Rogues of Norrath (please read some of the Rogues voicing their opinion loudest) start to call for nerfes of the Monk and the Ranger class and mainstreamwise deny their support for the Shaman class on the spell droprate topic.<br>
<br>
Basically I consider Rogues, Monks and Shamans well balanced, they are like the 100% level of classbalance. But, while still being the masters of longterm damage in the end game, Rogues started calling for nerfes of the Monk class (they showed a log that showed a topend Monk doing more than the 1.2 ratio compared to Warriors and a Rogue doing less than the 1.4 ratio). Sure, they often said not to nerf the Monks but to improve the Rogue damage even more, but that cannot be a solution since it would effect all other classes even more.<br>
After that, one Rogue found out that Rangers could outdamage Rogues with the use of their Trueshot discipline when having all available Alternative Advancements that benefit in this direction, the best gear and the most benefitting buffs. Rangers - put into a defensive position - are arguing against this at the moment.<br>
Meanwhile a Shaman asked on the Safehouse board to support his class in a petition to slightely up the drop rate of their level 60 spells in order to drop the prices on those spells a bit (those spells can go up to 100kpp) and the mainstream of the Rogues' answers was not very supportive - to use a polite wording.<br>
<br>
Well, that's the story I follow at the moment and the topic that boggles my mind (when thinking about EQ topics). I don't intend to deny a certain class its rights to state its opinion, and by no means its right to try to keep their status quo - against the Environment and against the other classes. And, as I said above, I don't say that all Rogues' opinion is displayed here.<br>
<br>
But: How far should this defense go? As far as the arguments against Necromancers, Paladins, int-casters in general pre-Kunark? Is the game-engine really that bad that you can't get another Rogue into the game in the highend game because of the uselessness of this class but rather put in lots of effords to get another Monk? As for the ToK-topic, is it really so bad that one formerly poor and roleless class gets a possibility to tune down the risk of a certain few encounters so that also smaller guilds can try to kill it?<br>
<br>
Please give me your opinion about all this. And please help to get this topic away from MithMarr to not allow another impact of efficience based selection of classes for xp-groups.<br>
<br>
